 PING (ping) [from TCP/IP terminology] n.,v. 1. Slang term for a small
network message (ICMP ECHO) sent by a computer to check for the presence and
aliveness of another. Occasionally used as a phone greeting. see ACK. 2. To
verify the presence of. 3. To get the attention of. From the Unix command by
the same name (an acronym of "Packet INternet Groper) that sends an ICMP ECHO
packet to another host. This was probably contrived to match WWII-era "ping"
(sonar ranging pulse).